value.value: The principal glutaminergic neuron located in the outer third of the external plexiform layer of the olfactory bulb; a single short primary dendrite traverses the outer external plexiform layer and terminates within an olfactory glomerulus in a tuft of branches, where it receives the input from olfactory receptor neuron axon terminals; axons of the tufted cells transfer information to a number of areas in the brain, including the piriform cortex, entorhinal cortex, olfactory tubercle, and amygdala.

The secretory neurons of the paraventricular nucleus that synthesize and secrete vasopressin, corticotropin-releasing factor (CRF) and thyrotropin-releasing hormone (TRH) into blood vessels in the hypothalamo-pituitary portal system.
The various hormone- or neurotransmitter-secreting cells present throughout the mucosa of the intestinal tract.
The various hormone- or neurotransmitter-secreting cells present throughout the mucosa of the stomach.
Any endothelial cell of vascular tree that is part of some lung.
Any endothelial cell of vascular tree that is part of some pulmonary artery.
An interneuron with a soma found in the hippocampus.
A pyramidal neuron with a soma found in the hippocampus.
A vascular endothelial cell found in colon blood vessels.
Cell of the nasopharyngeal epithelium.
Squamous cell of uterine cervix epithelium.
Squamous cell of oral epithelium.
Squamous cell of tonsil epithelium.
Squamous cell of vaginal epithelium.
Glial cell of cerebral cortex.
A glial cell that is part of the hippocampus.
Glial cell of lateral ventricle.
Neuron of lateral ventricle.
Glandular cell of appendix epithelium. Example: Goblet cells; enterocytes or absorptive cells; enteroendocrine and M cells.
Glandular cell of mammary epithelium. Example: glandular cells of large and intermediate ducts, glandular cells in terminal ducts.
Glandular cell of uterine cervix epithelium.
Glandular cell of colon epithelium. Example: Goblet cells; enterocytes or absorptive cells; enteroendocrine and M cells.
Glandular cell of duodenal epithelium. Example: Enterocytes, Goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells; Paneth cells; M cells; Brunner's gland cell.
Glandular cell of epididymal epithelium.
Glandular cell of oviduct epithelium. Example: peg cells, ciliated cells.
Glandular cell of gallbladder epithelium.
Glandular cell of parathyroid epithelium. Example: Parathyroid chief cell and parathyroid oxyphil cells.
Glandular cell of rectal epithelium. Example: Goblet cell; enterocytes or absorptive cells; enteroendocrine and M cells.

Glandular cell of salivary gland. Example: Serous cells, mucous cells, cuboidal epithelial cells of the intercalated ducts, simple cuboidal epithelium of the striated ducts, epithelial cells of excretory ducts.
Glandular cell of seminal vesicle epithelium.
A glandular cell found in the epithelium of the small intestine. Example: Enterocytes, Goblet cells, enteroendocrine cells; Paneth cells; M cells; Somatostatin-secreting Cells (D-cells) .
Glandular cell of exocrine pancreas epithelium. Example: pancreatic acinar cell, glandular cells in pancreatic canaliculi, glandular cells in pancreatic ducts.
Hormone secreting cell located in the cortex of adrenal gland. Glandular cells in the adrenal cortex secrete mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids and androgens.
Endothelial cells forming the walls of the capillaries within the cerebral cortex.
Circulating macrophages and tissue macrophages (alveolar macrophages) of lung.
Keratinocyte from foreskin.
Chondrocyte forming the hyaline cartilage found in joints.
Fibroblast from foreskin.
Fibroblast from muscle organ.

Hematopoietic cells resident in the bone marrow. Include: hematopoietic stem cells (lymphoid stem cells and myeloid stem cells) and the precursor cells for thrombocytes, erythrocytes, basophils, neutrophils, eosinophils, monocytes and lymphocytes.
Neuron of the cerebellum.
Any melanocyte that is part of a epidermis.

definition.value: These cells are found primarily, but not exclusively, in primates including humans

value.value: A leukocyte with a single non-segmented nucleus in the mature form found in the circulatory pool of blood.

A specialized, enlarged, connective tissue cell of the decidua with enlarged nucleus, dense membrane‐bound secretory granules and cytoplasmic accumulation of glycogen and lipid droplets. These cells develop by the transformation of endometrial stromal cells during decidualization.
Any cell that is part of a pituitary gland.
Any macroglial cell that is part of a brain.
Any germinal center B cell that is part of a tonsil.
Chondrocyte forming the hyaline cartilage found in the knee joint.
Any blood vessel endothelial cell that is part of a microvascular endothelium.
Any blood vessel endothelial cell that is part of a dermis.
